      "sectionId": 41,
      "sectionTitle": "The Exponential Function",
      "textbookSection": "I 6.9-6.13",
      "examples": [
        {
          "id": "ex-7-41-1",
          "type": "example",
          "title": "The Exponential as the Inverse of ln",
          "statement": "Define the exponential function $e^x$ as the inverse of $\\ln x$ and verify that $\\frac{d}{dx}[e^x] = e^x$.",
          "solution": {
            "steps": [
              {
                "title": "Define the Exponential",
                "content": "Since $\\ln x$ is strictly increasing on $(0, \\infty)$ with range $(-\\infty, \\infty)$, it has an inverse function.\n\nWe define $e^x$ (also written $\\exp(x)$) as this inverse:\n$$y = e^x \\iff x = \\ln y$$"
              },
              {
                "title": "Find the Derivative Using Implicit Differentiation",
                "content": "If $y = e^x$, then $\\ln y = x$.\n\nDifferentiate both sides with respect to $x$:\n$$\\frac{1}{y}\\frac{dy}{dx} = 1$$"
              },
              {
                "title": "Solve for dy/dx",
                "content": "$$\\frac{dy}{dx} = y = e^x$$\n\nThus $\\frac{d}{dx}[e^x] = e^x$."
              },
              {
                "title": "The Remarkable Property",
                "content": "The exponential function is its own derivative! This is the unique function (up to constant multiples) with this property."
              }
            ],
            "conclusion": "$\\frac{d}{dx}[e^x] = e^x$"
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "ex-7-41-2",
          "type": "example",
          "title": "General Exponential Functions",
          "statement": "For $a > 0$, define $a^x$ and find $\\frac{d}{dx}[a^x]$.",
          "solution": {
            "steps": [
              {
                "title": "Define a^x Using e",
                "content": "For any $a > 0$, we define:\n$$a^x = e^{x \\ln a}$$\n\nThis is consistent with integer and rational exponents."
              },
              {
                "title": "Differentiate Using the Chain Rule",
                "content": "$\\frac{d}{dx}[a^x] = \\frac{d}{dx}[e^{x \\ln a}]$\n\nLet $u = x \\ln a$, so $\\frac{du}{dx} = \\ln a$.\n\n$= e^{x \\ln a} \\cdot \\ln a = a^x \\ln a$"
              }
            ],
            "conclusion": "$\\frac{d}{dx}[a^x] = a^x \\ln a$"
          }
        }
      ],
      "exercises": [
